SSyynnooppssiiss
       #include <sys/types.h> #include <sys/mman.h>

       int mlock(void *addr, size_t len);

       int munlock(void *addr, size_t len);

DDeessccrriippttiioonn
       The  function  mlock uses the mappings established for the
       address range [addr, addr + len)

       to identify pages to be locked in memory.  The  effect  of
       mlock(addr, len)

       is equivalent to memcntl(addr, len, MC_LOCK, 0, 0, 0)

       munlock  removes locks established with mlock.  The effect
       of munlock(addr, len)

       is equivalent to memcntl(addr, len, MC_UNLOCK, 0, 0, 0)

       Locks established with mlock are not inherited by a  child
       process after a fork and are not nested.

   RReettuurrnn vvaalluueess
       Upon   successful  completion,  the  functions  mlock  and
       munlock return 0; otherwise, they return -1 and set  errno
       to indicate the error.

RReeffeerreenncceess
NNoottiicceess
       Use  of  mlock  and  munlock  requires  that the user have
       appropriate privileges.

